# CourtSense website

## Code quality

- Use TypeScript only (no plain JavaScript).
- Use functional components and hooks only.
- Keep components modular; avoid large monolithic files.

## Styling

- Use Tailwind utility classes only in components (no inline `style` except unavoidable SVG/radial cases).
- Follow the CJIS palette in `app/globals.css` (`--primary` navy, `--secondary` gold, background `#F8FAFC`).
- Prefer an 8px spacing rhythm (`gap-4`, `py-16`, etc.).

## Architecture

- Use the Next.js App Router only (no Pages Router).
- Prefer Server Components; mark `"use client"` only when hooks, Framer Motion, or browser APIs are required.
- Keep validation logic in `lib/` (e.g. `contact-schema.ts`).

## Performance

- Use `next/image` for raster assets when added.
- Avoid unnecessary client boundaries; lazy-load heavy client sections if they grow.

## UI / UX

- Enterprise simplicity: minimal motion; respect `prefers-reduced-motion` (see `FadeInSection`).
- Provide accessible labels, landmarks, and skip links.

## Naming

- Components: PascalCase. Files: kebab-case or PascalCase for components. Variables: camelCase.

## Security & privacy

- No external analytics or tracking scripts.
- Do not add dependencies without clear need.
- No hardcoded secrets; use env templates for future APIs.

## Tone

- Institutional, formal copy. Emphasize efficiency, accuracy, and security—not hype.
